04332nam a22006495i 9780804787147DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202013cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2013018102  a97808047871477 a10.1515/97808047871472doi  a(DE-B1597)564658  a(OCoLC)1198931565  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aDC34.5.A4bL96 2013 4aDC34.5.A4bL96 2013 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a305.892765044090452231 aLyons, Amelia H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Civilizing Mission in the Metropole :bAlgerian Families and the French Welfare State during Decolonization /cAmelia H. Lyons. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and table -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Civilizing "french Muslims from Algeria" -- t2. Instructing the experts: framing the metropolitan "conquest of hearts" -- t3. Instructing a "difficult and delicate clientele": the social services mission -- t4. From dormitories to homes: housing workers and families during the fourth republic -- t5. Services and surveillance: welfare, the police, and the Algerian war -- t6. The great "hope": housing Algerian families at the height of the Algerian war -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrance, which has the largest Muslim minority community in Europe, has been in the news in recent years because of perceptions that Muslims have not integrated into French society. The Civilizing Mission in the Metropole explores the roots of these debates through an examination of the history of social welfare programs for Algerian migrants from the end of World War II until Algeria gained independence in 1962. After its colonization in 1830, Algeria fought a bloody war of decolonization against France, as France desperately fought to maintain control over its most prized imperial possession. In the midst of this violence, some 350,000 Algerians settled in France. This study examines the complex and often-contradictory goals of a welfare network that sought to provide services and monitor Algerian migrants' activities. Lyons particularly highlights family settlement and the central place Algerian women held in French efforts to transform the settled community. Lyons questions myths about Algerian immigration history and exposes numerous paradoxes surrounding the fraught relationship between France and Algeria-many of which echo in French debates about Muslims today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAlgeriansxGovernment policyzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aWelfare statezFrancexHistoryy20th century. 4aAlgerian War (1954-1962). 4aAlgerians. 4aFifth Republic. 4aForth Republic. 4aFrance. 4acivilizing mission. 4adecolonization. 4asocial welfare. 4awomen. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804787147zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804787147423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804787147.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles